The try-catch-finally block is used in exception handling to catch and handle exceptions that may occur during the execution of a code block. The structure typically looks like this:

```
try {
    // Code that may throw an exception
} catch (ExceptionType1 e1) {
    // Code to handle ExceptionType1
} catch (ExceptionType2 e2) {
    // Code to handle ExceptionType2
} finally {
    // Code that will always execute, regardless of whether an exception occurred or not
}
```

In this structure, the code within the try block is executed. If an exception of type ExceptionType1 occurs, the catch block for ExceptionType1 is executed. If an exception of type ExceptionType2 occurs, the catch block for ExceptionType2 is executed. The finally block is optional and will always execute, regardless of whether an exception occurred or not.

