One faster alternative to file_get_contents() is using the cURL library. cURL is a powerful library that allows you to make HTTP requests and retrieve the content of a file or webpage. It is generally faster than file_get_contents() because it is optimized for handling network requests.

Here's an example of how you can use cURL to retrieve the content of a file:

```php
function get_file_contents($url) {
    $ch = curl_init();
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, $url);
    curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);
    $content = curl_exec($ch);
    curl_close($ch);
    return $content;
}

$fileContent = get_file_contents('https://example.com/file.txt');
```

In this example, the get_file_contents() function takes a URL as a parameter and uses cURL to retrieve the content of the file at that URL. The CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER option tells cURL to return the content as a string instead of outputting it directly.

Using cURL can provide better performance and more control over the HTTP request compared to file_get_contents(). However, keep in mind that cURL requires the cURL extension to be enabled in your PHP installation.

