To crop an image in PHP, you can use the GD library. Here's an example of how you can crop an image:

```php
// Path to the image file
$imagePath = 'path/to/image.jpg';

// Load the image
$image = imagecreatefromjpeg($imagePath);

// Get the current dimensions of the image
$width = imagesx($image);
$height = imagesy($image);

// Set the desired dimensions for the cropped image
$cropWidth = 200;
$cropHeight = 200;

// Calculate the coordinates for the crop
$cropX = ($width - $cropWidth) / 2;
$cropY = ($height - $cropHeight) / 2;

// Create a new image with the desired dimensions
$croppedImage = imagecreatetruecolor($cropWidth, $cropHeight);

// Crop the image
imagecopyresampled($croppedImage, $image, 0, 0, $cropX, $cropY, $cropWidth, $cropHeight, $cropWidth, $cropHeight);

// Save the cropped image to a file
$croppedImagePath = 'path/to/cropped_image.jpg';
imagejpeg($croppedImage, $croppedImagePath);

// Free up memory
imagedestroy($image);
imagedestroy($croppedImage);
```

In this example, we first load the image using `imagecreatefromjpeg()` function. Then, we get the current dimensions of the image using `imagesx()` and `imagesy()` functions.

Next, we set the desired dimensions for the cropped image. In this case, we set it to 200x200 pixels. We calculate the coordinates for the crop by subtracting the desired dimensions from the current dimensions and dividing by 2.

We create a new image with the desired dimensions using `imagecreatetruecolor()` function. Then, we use `imagecopyresampled()` function to crop the image based on the calculated coordinates.

Finally, we save the cropped image to a file using `imagejpeg()` function and free up memory using `imagedestroy()` function.

