To send a multipart form data PUT request in PHP, you can use the `curl` library. Here's an example:

```php
// Create a new cURL resource
$ch = curl_init();

// Set the URL
curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_URL, 'http://example.com/api/endpoint');

// Set the request method to PUT
curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST, 'PUT');

// Set the request body as multipart form data
$data = array(
    'field1' => 'value1',
    'field2' => 'value2',
    'file' => new CURLFile('/path/to/file.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 'file.jpg')
);
curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS, $data);

// Set additional headers if needed
curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER, array(
    'Content-Type: multipart/form-data'
));

// Execute the request
$response = curl_exec($ch);

// Check for errors
if ($response === false) {
    echo 'cURL error: ' . curl_error($ch);
}

// Close cURL resource
curl_close($ch);

// Handle the response
echo $response;
```

In this example, we are using the `curl_setopt` function to set various options for the cURL request. The `CURLOPT_URL` option sets the URL of the API endpoint. The `CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST` option sets the request method to PUT. The `CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS` option sets the request body as an array of form data. The `CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER` option sets the Content-Type header to `multipart/form-data`.

Make sure to replace `'http://example.com/api/endpoint'` with the actual URL of your API endpoint, and `'field1'`, `'value1'`, `'field2'`, `'value2'`, `'/path/to/file.jpg'`, `'image/jpeg'`, and `'file.jpg'` with the actual field names, values, and file path.

Note: The `CURLFile` class is available in PHP 5.5 and later. If you are using an older version of PHP, you can use the `@` prefix to specify the file path instead (e.g., `'file' => '@/path/to/file.jpg'`). However, using the `@` prefix is deprecated in PHP 5.5 and removed in PHP 7.0, so it's recommended to use the `CURLFile` class if possible.

