In Laravel, the `whenLoaded()` method allows you to check if a relationship has been loaded and perform additional operations on it. By default, `whenLoaded()` only works for direct relationships. However, you can use the `with()` method to load nested relationships and then use `whenLoaded()` on those nested relationships.

Here's an example of how you can use `whenLoaded()` on nested relationships:

```php
$users = User::with('posts.comments')->get();

$users->each(function ($user) {
    $user->whenLoaded('posts.comments', function ($posts) {
        $posts->each(function ($post) {
            $post->whenLoaded('comments', function ($comments) {
                // Perform additional operations on comments
                $comments->each(function ($comment) {
                    // Do something with each comment
                });
            });
        });
    });
});
```

In this example, we are loading the `posts` relationship along with its nested `comments` relationship using the `with()` method. Then, we iterate over each user and use `whenLoaded()` to check if the `posts.comments` relationship has been loaded. If it has, we can perform additional operations on the comments.

Note that `whenLoaded()` is a conditional method, so the callback will only be executed if the relationship has been loaded. If the relationship has not been loaded, the callback will not be executed.

You can nest `whenLoaded()` calls as deep as necessary to handle multiple levels of nested relationships.

