In PHP, you can create a custom error handler to handle parse and fatal errors. This allows you to handle these errors in a way that suits your application's needs.

To create a custom error handler, you need to define a function that will be called whenever an error occurs. This function should have the following signature:

```php
function customErrorHandler($errno, $errstr, $errfile, $errline)
```

The parameters of this function are as follows:

- `$errno`: The level of the error raised, represented by an integer value.
- `$errstr`: The error message.
- `$errfile`: The filename where the error occurred.
- `$errline`: The line number where the error occurred.

Inside the custom error handler function, you can perform any actions you want, such as logging the error, sending an email notification, or displaying a custom error page.

Here's an example of a custom error handler that logs parse and fatal errors:

```php
function customErrorHandler($errno, $errstr, $errfile, $errline) {
    // Log the error
    error_log("Error: $errstr in $errfile on line $errline");

    // Display a custom error page or message
    echo "An error occurred. Please try again later.";

    // Prevent the default PHP error handler from executing
    return true;
}

// Set the custom error handler
set_error_handler("customErrorHandler");

// Enable error reporting for parse errors
ini_set("display_errors", 0);
ini_set("display_startup_errors", 0);
error_reporting(E_PARSE);

// Enable error reporting for fatal errors
register_shutdown_function(function() {
    $error = error_get_last();
    if ($error !== null && $error['type'] === E_ERROR) {
        customErrorHandler($error['type'], $error['message'], $error['file'], $error['line']);
    }
});
```

In this example, the `customErrorHandler` function logs the error using the `error_log` function and displays a custom error message. The `return true` statement prevents the default PHP error handler from executing.

To handle parse errors, we disable the display of errors using the `ini_set` function and enable error reporting specifically for parse errors using the `error_reporting` function.

To handle fatal errors, we register a shutdown function using the `register_shutdown_function` function. This function is called when the script execution ends, allowing us to check if a fatal error occurred using the `error_get_last` function. If a fatal error occurred, we call the `customErrorHandler` function with the appropriate error details.

Remember to include this custom error handler code at the beginning of your PHP script or in a separate file that is included in all your PHP scripts.

In Laravel 4, you can inject multiple classes that share the same interface by using the `bind` method in the service container. Here's how you can do it:

1. Define the interface:
   ```php
   // app/Contracts/MyInterface.php
   namespace App\Contracts;

   interface MyInterface {
       // define your interface methods here
   }
   ```

2. Implement the interface in multiple classes:
   ```php
   // app/Classes/ClassA.php
   namespace App\Classes;

   use App\Contracts\MyInterface;

   class ClassA implements MyInterface {
       // implement the interface methods here
   }

   // app/Classes/ClassB.php
   namespace App\Classes;

   use App\Contracts\MyInterface;

   class ClassB implements MyInterface {
       // implement the interface methods here
   }
   ```

3. Bind the interface to the classes in the service container:
   ```php
   // app/start/global.php
   use App\Contracts\MyInterface;
   use App\Classes\ClassA;
   use App\Classes\ClassB;

   $app->bind(MyInterface::class, function ($app) {
       return [
           $app->make(ClassA::class),
           $app->make(ClassB::class),
       ];
   });
   ```

4. Inject the interface in your controller or other classes:
   ```php
   // app/Http/Controllers/MyController.php
   namespace App\Http\Controllers;

   use App\Contracts\MyInterface;

   class MyController extends Controller {
       protected $myInterface;

       public function __construct(MyInterface $myInterface) {
           $this->myInterface = $myInterface;
       }

       // use the $myInterface instance in your controller methods
   }
   ```

Now, when you resolve the `MyController` class from the service container, it will automatically inject an array containing instances of `ClassA` and `ClassB` that implement the `MyInterface`.

To combine two models into one paginated query with eager loaded relations using Laravel, you can use the `with` method along with the `paginate` method. Here's an example:

```php
use App\Models\Model1;
use App\Models\Model2;

$perPage = 10; // Number of records per page

$query = Model1::with('relation1')
    ->join('model2', 'model1.id', '=', 'model2.model1_id')
    ->with('relation2')
    ->select('model1.*')
    ->paginate($perPage);

// Access the results
$results = $query->items();

// Access the pagination links
$links = $query->links();
```

In this example, we are combining `Model1` and `Model2` into one query by joining them on a common column (`model1.id` and `model2.model1_id`). We are eager loading the relations `relation1` and `relation2` using the `with` method.

The `select` method is used to select only the columns from `Model1` to avoid duplicate columns in the result set.

Finally, we use the `paginate` method to paginate the results with the specified number of records per page.

You can access the paginated results using the `items` method, and the pagination links using the `links` method.

To send an email using PHP on Windows Azure, you can follow these steps:

1. Set up an SMTP server: Windows Azure does not provide an SMTP server by default, so you will need to set up an external SMTP server. You can use services like SendGrid, Mailgun, or any other SMTP service provider.

2. Install the required PHP libraries: You will need to install the necessary PHP libraries to send emails. The most commonly used library is PHPMailer. You can download it from the official GitHub repository or use Composer to install it.

3. Configure PHPMailer: Once you have PHPMailer installed, you need to configure it with your SMTP server credentials. Here's an example of how to configure PHPMailer with SendGrid:

```php
require 'vendor/autoload.php';

$mail = new PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer();
$mail->isSMTP();
$mail->Host = 'smtp.sendgrid.net';
$mail->SMTPAuth = true;
$mail->Username = 'your_sendgrid_username';
$mail->Password = 'your_sendgrid_password';
$mail->SMTPSecure = 'tls';
$mail->Port = 587;
```

Replace `'your_sendgrid_username'` and `'your_sendgrid_password'` with your actual SendGrid credentials.

4. Compose and send the email: After configuring PHPMailer, you can compose and send the email using the following code:

```php
$mail->setFrom('from@example.com', 'Your Name');
$mail->addAddress('recipient@example.com', 'Recipient Name');
$mail->Subject = 'Email Subject';
$mail->Body = 'Email body content';

if ($mail->send()) {
    echo 'Email sent successfully';
} else {
    echo 'Error sending email: ' . $mail->ErrorInfo;
}
```

Replace `'from@example.com'` with your email address and `'recipient@example.com'` with the recipient's email address.

5. Test the email sending: Finally, you can test the email sending functionality by running the PHP script on your Windows Azure server. Make sure you have the necessary permissions and firewall rules configured to allow outgoing SMTP connections.

Note: The above steps assume you have a basic understanding of PHP and Windows Azure. If you are new to PHP or Windows Azure, you may need to refer to the respective documentation for more detailed instructions.

