To resize images using PHP, you can use the GD library. Here's an example code that supports both PNG and JPG image formats:

```php
<?php
function resizeImage($sourceImage, $targetImage, $maxWidth, $maxHeight, $quality = 80) {
    // Get the original image dimensions
    list($sourceWidth, $sourceHeight, $sourceType) = getimagesize($sourceImage);

    // Calculate the aspect ratio
    $aspectRatio = $sourceWidth / $sourceHeight;

    // Calculate the new dimensions based on the maximum width and height
    if ($maxWidth / $maxHeight > $aspectRatio) {
        $newWidth = $maxHeight * $aspectRatio;
        $newHeight = $maxHeight;
    } else {
        $newWidth = $maxWidth;
        $newHeight = $maxWidth / $aspectRatio;
    }

    // Create a new image resource based on the source image type
    switch ($sourceType) {
        case IMAGETYPE_JPEG:
            $sourceImageResource = imagecreatefromjpeg($sourceImage);
            break;
        case IMAGETYPE_PNG:
            $sourceImageResource = imagecreatefrompng($sourceImage);
            break;
        default:
            return false; // Unsupported image type
    }

    // Create a new image resource with the new dimensions
    $targetImageResource = imagecreatetruecolor($newWidth, $newHeight);

    // Preserve transparency for PNG images
    if ($sourceType == IMAGETYPE_PNG) {
        imagealphablending($targetImageResource, false);
        imagesavealpha($targetImageResource, true);
        $transparent = imagecolorallocatealpha($targetImageResource, 255, 255, 255, 127);
        imagefilledrectangle($targetImageResource, 0, 0, $newWidth, $newHeight, $transparent);
    }

    // Resize the image
    imagecopyresampled($targetImageResource, $sourceImageResource, 0, 0, 0, 0, $newWidth, $newHeight, $sourceWidth, $sourceHeight);

    // Save the resized image
    switch ($sourceType) {
        case IMAGETYPE_JPEG:
            imagejpeg($targetImageResource, $targetImage, $quality);
            break;
        case IMAGETYPE_PNG:
            imagepng($targetImageResource, $targetImage);
            break;
    }

    // Free up memory
    imagedestroy($sourceImageResource);
    imagedestroy($targetImageResource);

    return true;
}

// Usage example
$sourceImage = 'path/to/source/image.jpg';
$targetImage = 'path/to/target/image.jpg';
$maxWidth = 800;
$maxHeight = 600;
$quality = 80;

resizeImage($sourceImage, $targetImage, $maxWidth, $maxHeight, $quality);
?>
```

Make sure to replace `'path/to/source/image.jpg'` with the actual path to your source image and `'path/to/target/image.jpg'` with the desired path for the resized image.

You can adjust the `$maxWidth`, `$maxHeight`, and `$quality` variables according to your requirements.

