In Laravel, you can add check constraints to a table using migrations. Check constraints are used to enforce certain conditions on the data being inserted or updated in a table.

To add a check constraint in a Laravel migration, you can use the `DB::statement()` method to execute a raw SQL query. Here's an example of how you can add a check constraint to a table:

```php
use Illuminate\Database\Migrations\Migration;
use Illuminate\Database\Schema\Blueprint;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\DB;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Schema;

class AddCheckConstraintToTable extends Migration
{
    /**
     * Run the migrations.
