In PhpStorm, when you access a field via a magic method, such as `__get()` or `__set()`, PhpStorm may not be able to provide accurate code completion and analysis for that field.

This is because PhpStorm's code analysis is based on static analysis, which means it analyzes the code without actually executing it. Magic methods, on the other hand, are called dynamically at runtime, and their behavior can vary depending on the specific implementation.

To help PhpStorm understand the dynamic behavior of magic methods, you can use PHPDoc annotations to provide type hints for the accessed field. For example, you can use the `@property` annotation to specify the type of a field accessed via `__get()`:

```php
/**
 * @property string $myField
 */
class MyClass {
    private $data = [];

    public function __get($name) {
        return $this->data[$name];
    }
}
```

By adding the `@property` annotation, PhpStorm will now recognize `$myField` as a string and provide accurate code completion and analysis for it.

Similarly, you can use the `@property-write` annotation to specify the type of a field accessed via `__set()`:

```php
/**
 * @property-write string $myField
 */
class MyClass {
    private $data = [];

    public function __set($name, $value) {
        $this->data[$name] = $value;
    }
}
```

Again, by adding the `@property-write` annotation, PhpStorm will now recognize `$myField` as a string and provide accurate code completion and analysis for it when setting its value.

Note that these annotations are only hints for PhpStorm and do not affect the actual behavior of the magic methods at runtime. They are simply used to improve the IDE's understanding of the code and provide better code completion and analysis.

