In PHP, exception chaining can be implemented using the `Throwable` interface and the `Throwable` constructor. Here's how you can do it:

1. Create a custom exception class that extends the built-in `Exception` class or any other exception class you want to use. This class will be used to throw and catch exceptions.

```php
class CustomException extends Exception {
    public function __construct($message = "", $code = 0, Throwable $previous = null) {
        parent::__construct($message, $code, $previous);
    }
}
```

2. Throw an instance of the custom exception class with the previous exception as an argument. This will create a chain of exceptions.

```php
try {
    // Code that may throw an exception
    throw new CustomException("Something went wrong", 0, $previousException);
} catch (CustomException $e) {
    // Handle the exception
    echo $e->getMessage();
    echo $e->getPrevious()->getMessage(); // Access the previous exception's message
}
```

3. You can also catch and re-throw exceptions to create a chain of exceptions. This can be useful when you want to add additional information to an exception before re-throwing it.

```php
try {
    // Code that may throw an exception
    throw new CustomException("Something went wrong");
} catch (CustomException $e) {
    // Handle the exception
    echo $e->getMessage();

    // Add additional information to the exception
    $e->addAdditionalInfo("Additional information");

    // Re-throw the exception
