To avoid resending data on refresh in PHP, you can use the Post/Redirect/Get (PRG) pattern. This pattern involves the following steps:

1. When the form is submitted, process the data and perform the necessary actions (e.g., saving to a database).
2. After processing the data, redirect the user to a different page using the `header()` function in PHP. This page can be a success page or the same page without the form.
   ```php
   header("Location: success.php");
   exit;
   ```
3. On the redirected page, display the success message or perform any other necessary actions.

By redirecting the user after processing the form data, you prevent the form from being resubmitted when the user refreshes the page. This way, refreshing the page will only reload the redirected page without resending the data.

Additionally, you can also use the `$_SESSION` superglobal to store the form data temporarily and retrieve it on the redirected page. This way, you can display the submitted data on the success page without relying on form resubmission.

Here's an example of how you can implement the PRG pattern in PHP:

```php
// form.php
<?php
session_start();

if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    // Process the form data and perform necessary actions
    $name = $_POST["name"];
    $email = $_POST["email"];

    // Store the form data in session
    $_SESSION["form_data"] = $_POST;

    // Redirect to success page
    header("Location: success.php");
    exit;
}
?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Form</title>
</head>
<body>
    <form method="POST" action="<?php echo $_SERVER["PHP_SELF"]; ?>">
        <input type="text" name="name" placeholder="Name" required><br>
        <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><br>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
</body>
</html>

// success.php
<?php
session_start();

// Retrieve the form data from session
$formData = $_SESSION["form_data"];

// Clear the form data from session
unset($_SESSION["form_data"]);
?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Success</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Success!</h1>
    <p>Name: <?php echo $formData["name"]; ?></p>
    <p>Email: <?php echo $formData["email"]; ?></p>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the form data is stored in the `$_SESSION["form_data"]` variable before redirecting to the success page. On the success page, the form data is retrieved from the session and displayed.

