To manually parse raw multipart/form-data data with PHP, you can follow these steps:

1. Get the raw data from the request:
```php
$rawData = file_get_contents('php://input');
```

2. Split the raw data into individual parts using the boundary string:
```php
$boundary = substr($rawData, 0, strpos($rawData, "\r\n"));
$parts = array_slice(explode($boundary, $rawData), 1);
```

3. Iterate over each part and extract the headers and content:
```php
$data = array();
foreach ($parts as $part) {
    // Split the part into headers and content
    list($rawHeaders, $content) = explode("\r\n\r\n", $part, 2);

    // Parse the headers
    $headers = array();
    foreach (explode("\r\n", $rawHeaders) as $header) {
        list($name, $value) = explode(':', $header, 2);
        $headers[$name] = trim($value);
    }

    // Extract the name and filename from the Content-Disposition header
    preg_match('/name="([^"]+)"(; filename="([^"]+)")?/', $headers['Content-Disposition'], $matches);
    $name = $matches[1];
    $filename = isset($matches[3]) ? $matches[3] : null;

    // Store the content in the data array
    $data[] = array(
        'name' => $name,
        'filename' => $filename,
        'content' => $content
    );
}
```

4. You can now access the parsed data in the `$data` array. For example, to get the content of a field named "username":
```php
foreach ($data as $part) {
    if ($part['name'] === 'username') {
        $username = $part['content'];
        break;
    }
}
```

Note: This is a basic example and may not handle all possible scenarios. It assumes that the raw data is properly formatted and follows the multipart/form-data specification.

