In C#, you can use the `Split` and `Join` methods as alternatives to PHP's `explode` and `implode` functions.

1. Alternative to `explode` function:
   In PHP, `explode` splits a string into an array using a delimiter. In C#, you can achieve the same functionality using the `Split` method of the `String` class.

   ```csharp
   string input = "Hello,World,!";
   char delimiter = ',';
   string[] result = input.Split(delimiter);
   ```

   The `result` array will contain the split parts of the string.

2. Alternative to `implode` function:
   In PHP, `implode` joins array elements into a string using a delimiter. In C#, you can achieve the same functionality using the `Join` method of the `String` class.

   ```csharp
   string[] input = { "Hello", "World", "!" };
   char delimiter = ',';
   string result = string.Join(delimiter.ToString(), input);
   ```

   The `result` string will contain the joined elements of the array.

Note: In C#, the `Split` and `Join` methods are part of the `String` class, so you need to use them with a string object or a string literal.

The '&=' operator is a compound assignment operator that performs a bitwise AND operation between two operands and assigns the result to the left operand. It is equivalent to the expression `a = a & b`, where 'a' and 'b' are variables.

Example:
```
int a = 5;
int b = 3;
a &= b; // equivalent to a = a & b;
// After this operation, the value of 'a' will be 1 (binary 001)
```

The '=&' operator, on the other hand, is not a valid operator in most programming languages. It seems like a typo or a mistake.

To return JSON encoded form errors in Symfony, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a new class that extends the `JsonResponse` class provided by Symfony. This class will handle the JSON encoding of the form errors.

```php
use Symfony\Component\HttpFoundation\JsonResponse;

class FormErrorJsonResponse extends JsonResponse
{
    public function __construct($data = null, int $status = 200, array $headers = [], bool $json = false)
    {
        parent::__construct($data, $status, $headers, $json);

        $this->setData([
            'success' => false,
            'errors' => $data,
        ]);
    }
}
```

2. In your controller action, handle the form submission and return the JSON encoded form errors if there are any.

```php
use App\Form\YourFormType;
use Symfony\Component\HttpFoundation\Request;
use Symfony\Component\Routing\Annotation\Route;

/**
 * @Route("/your-route", name="your_route", methods={"POST"})
 */
public function yourAction(Request $request)
{
    $form = $this->createForm(YourFormType::class);
    $form->handleRequest($request);

    if ($form->isSubmitted() && !$form->isValid()) {
        $errors = $this->getFormErrors($form);

        return new FormErrorJsonResponse($errors, 400);
    }

    // Handle the valid form submission

    return new JsonResponse(['success' => true]);
}

private function getFormErrors(FormInterface $form): array
{
    $errors = [];

    foreach ($form->getErrors() as $error) {
        $errors[] = $error->getMessage();
    }

    foreach ($form->all() as $childForm) {
        if ($childForm instanceof FormInterface) {
            if ($childErrors = $this->getFormErrors($childForm)) {
                $errors[$childForm->getName()] = $childErrors;
            }
        }
    }

    return $errors;
}
```

3. In your form template, you can display the form errors using JavaScript or any other method you prefer.

```twig
{{ form_start(form) }}
{{ form_widget(form) }}
{{ form_end(form) }}

{% if form.vars.errors|length > 0 %}
    <script>
        var formErrors = {{ form.vars.errors|json_encode|raw }};
        // Handle the form errors
    </script>
{% endif %}
```

With these steps, you can return JSON encoded form errors in Symfony and handle them on the client-side.

