To use Socket.io in a server other than localhost (such as WAMP or XAMPP), you need to follow these steps:

1. Install Node.js on your server: Download and install Node.js from the official website (https://nodejs.org/).

2. Create a new directory for your project: Open a terminal or command prompt and navigate to the desired directory. Use the following command to create a new directory:
   ```
   mkdir my-socketio-project
   ```

3. Initialize a new Node.js project: Navigate into the newly created directory and run the following command to initialize a new Node.js project:
   ```
   cd my-socketio-project
   npm init -y
   ```

4. Install Socket.io: Run the following command to install Socket.io in your project:
   ```
   npm install socket.io
   ```

5. Create a server file: Create a new file called `server.js` in your project directory and add the following code:
   ```javascript
   const express = require('express');
   const app = express();
   const http = require('http').Server(app);
   const io = require('socket.io')(http);

   app.get('/', (req, res) => {
     res.sendFile(__dirname + '/index.html');
   });

   io.on('connection', (socket) => {
     console.log('A user connected');
     socket.on('disconnect', () => {
       console.log('A user disconnected');
     });
   });

   http.listen(3000, () => {
     console.log('Server is running on http://localhost:3000');
   });
   ```

6. Create an HTML file: Create a new file called `index.html` in your project directory and add the following code:
   ```html
   <html>
   <head>
     <script src="/socket.io/socket.io.js"></script>
     <script>
       const socket = io();

       socket.on('connect', () => {
         console.log('Connected to server');
       });

       socket.on('disconnect', () => {
         console.log('Disconnected from server');
       });
     </script>
   </head>
   <body>
     <h1>Socket.io Example</h1>
   </body>
   </html>
   ```

7. Start the server: Run the following command to start the server:
   ```
   node server.js
   ```

8. Access the server: Open a web browser and navigate to `http://your-server-ip:3000`. You should see the "Socket.io Example" heading in the browser's console.

Note: Replace `your-server-ip` with the actual IP address or domain name of your server.

That's it! You have successfully set up a Socket.io server on a server other than localhost.

In PHPUnit, you cannot directly acquire a reference to the `$GLOBALS` superglobal variable. This is because PHPUnit runs tests in an isolated environment, and accessing global variables directly would break the isolation and make the tests less reliable.

However, you can still access global variables indirectly by using a wrapper function or a helper class. Here's an example of how you can access the `$GLOBALS` variable indirectly in PHPUnit:

```php
class GlobalWrapper
{
    public static function getGlobal($key)
    {
        return $GLOBALS[$key];
    }
}
```

Then, in your test case, you can use the `GlobalWrapper` class to access the `$GLOBALS` variable:

```php
class MyTest extends \PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase
{
    public function testGlobalVariable()
    {
        $GLOBALS['myVar'] = 'Hello World';

        $value = GlobalWrapper::getGlobal('myVar');

        $this->assertEquals('Hello World', $value);
    }
}
```

By using this approach, you can indirectly access the `$GLOBALS` variable in your PHPUnit tests without breaking the isolation provided by PHPUnit.

