To add Node.js for real-time notifications to an existing PHP application, you can follow these steps:

1. Install Node.js: Download and install Node.js from the official website (https://nodejs.org). Follow the installation instructions for your operating system.

2. Create a new directory: Create a new directory in your PHP application's root directory to hold your Node.js code. For example, you can create a directory called "node" or "realtime".

3. Initialize Node.js: Open a terminal or command prompt, navigate to the newly created directory, and run the following command to initialize a new Node.js project:
   ```
   npm init
   ```

   This command will prompt you to enter some details about your project. You can press enter to accept the default values or provide your own.

4. Install required packages: Install the necessary packages for real-time functionality. In this case, we will use the popular Socket.IO library. Run the following command to install it:
   ```
   npm install socket.io
   ```

5. Create a Node.js server file: Create a new file in the Node.js directory, for example, "server.js". This file will contain the code for your Node.js server.

6. Write the Node.js server code: Open the "server.js" file and write the following code to create a basic Node.js server using Socket.IO:
   ```javascript
   const http = require('http');
   const server = http.createServer();
   const io = require('socket.io')(server);

   io.on('connection', (socket) => {
     console.log('A user connected');

     socket.on('disconnect', () => {
       console.log('A user disconnected');
     });
   });

   server.listen(3000, () => {
     console.log('Node.js server running on port 3000');
   });
   ```

   This code sets up a basic Socket.IO server that listens for client connections and disconnections.

7. Integrate Node.js with PHP: In your PHP application, you can now add the necessary JavaScript code to connect to the Node.js server and handle real-time notifications. You can include the following code in your PHP templates or scripts:
   ```html
   <script src="http://localhost:3000/socket.io/socket.io.js"></script>
   <script>
     const socket = io('http://localhost:3000');

     socket.on('connect', () => {
       console.log('Connected to Node.js server');
     });

     socket.on('notification', (data) => {
       console.log('Received notification:', data);
       // Handle the notification as needed
     });
   </script>
   ```

   This code includes the Socket.IO client library and establishes a connection to the Node.js server. It also listens for the 'notification' event and handles it accordingly.

8. Start the Node.js server: In the terminal or command prompt, navigate to the Node.js directory and run the following command to start the Node.js server:
   ```
   node server.js
   ```

   You should see the message "Node.js server running on port 3000" indicating that the server is running.

9. Test the real-time notifications: Load your PHP application in a web browser and check the browser's console. You should see the message "Connected to Node.js server" indicating that the client successfully connected to the Node.js server. You can now emit 'notification' events from the server to trigger real-time notifications in the PHP application.

That's it! You have successfully added Node.js for real-time notifications to your existing PHP application. You can now customize the server-side and client-side code to suit your specific requirements.

