To get the version from an Android .apk file using PHP, you can use the following code:

```php
<?php
$apkFilePath = 'path/to/your/app.apk';

// Open the .apk file
$zip = new ZipArchive;
if ($zip->open($apkFilePath) === true) {
    // Read the AndroidManifest.xml file from the .apk
    $manifest = $zip->getFromName('AndroidManifest.xml');

    // Close the .apk file
    $zip->close();

    // Extract the versionName attribute from the AndroidManifest.xml
    $pattern = '/versionName="(.*?)"/';
    preg_match($pattern, $manifest, $matches);

    // Check if the versionName attribute was found
    if (isset($matches[1])) {
        $version = $matches[1];
        echo "Version: " . $version;
    } else {
        echo "Version not found.";
    }
} else {
    echo "Failed to open the .apk file.";
}
?>
```

Make sure to replace `'path/to/your/app.apk'` with the actual path to your .apk file. This code uses the `ZipArchive` class to open the .apk file, reads the `AndroidManifest.xml` file from it, and extracts the `versionName` attribute using regular expressions.

