In Laravel 5.4, you cannot access the `Auth::user()` method directly in the constructor of a controller. This is because the middleware that handles authentication has not been run yet at the time the constructor is called.

To access the authenticated user in the constructor, you can use the `middleware` method provided by Laravel. Here's an example:

```php
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;

class YourController extends Controller
{
    public function __construct()
    {
        $this->middleware(function ($request, $next) {
            $this->user = Auth::user();
            return $next($request);
        });
    }

    public function yourMethod()
    {
        // You can now access $this->user here
    }
}
```

In the above example, we define a closure in the constructor using the `middleware` method. This closure will be executed before any other methods in the controller. Inside the closure, we can access the authenticated user using `Auth::user()` and store it in a property (`$this->user` in this case) for later use.

Now, you can access the authenticated user in any method of the controller using `$this->user`.

