To make an asynchronous GET request in PHP, you can use the `curl` library. Here's an example of how you can do it:

```php
// Create a new cURL resource
$curl = curl_init();

// Set the URL and other options
curl_setopt($curl, CURLOPT_URL, 'https://example.com/api');
curl_setopt($curl, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true);
curl_setopt($curl, CURLOPT_HEADER, false);

// Set the request to be asynchronous
curl_setopt($curl, CURLOPT_FRESH_CONNECT, true);
curl_setopt($curl, CURLOPT_TIMEOUT_MS, 1);

// Execute the request asynchronously
curl_exec($curl);

// Close the cURL resource
curl_close($curl);
```

In this example, we use the `curl_init()` function to create a new cURL resource. Then, we set the URL of the API endpoint we want to make a GET request to using `curl_setopt()`. We also set `CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER` to `true` to return the response as a string instead of outputting it directly.

To make the request asynchronous, we set `CURLOPT_FRESH_CONNECT` to `true` to ensure a new connection is made for each request, and `CURLOPT_TIMEOUT_MS` to a very low value (1 millisecond in this case) to make the request timeout almost immediately.

Finally, we execute the request using `curl_exec()` and close the cURL resource using `curl_close()`.

To remove `index.php` from the URL and avoid a redirect loop in Nginx, you can use the following configuration:

1. Open your Nginx configuration file. The location of this file may vary depending on your operating system and Nginx installation. Common locations include `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf`, `/etc/nginx/sites-available/default`, or `/etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf`.

2. Inside the `server` block, add the following lines:

```nginx
location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php?$query_string;
}

location ~ \.php$ {
    include snippets/fastcgi-php.conf;
    fastcgi_pass unix:/var/run/php/php7.4-fpm.sock;
    fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
    include fastcgi_params;
}
```

3. Save the configuration file and exit.

4. Restart Nginx to apply the changes. The command to restart Nginx may vary depending on your operating system. Common commands include `sudo service nginx restart`, `sudo systemctl restart nginx`, or `sudo /etc/init.d/nginx restart`.

With this configuration, Nginx will try to serve the requested file directly. If the file doesn't exist, it will try to serve the corresponding directory. If that also doesn't exist, it will pass the request to `index.php` with the original query string.

Make sure to replace `/var/run/php/php7.4-fpm.sock` with the correct path to your PHP-FPM socket file. Additionally, adjust other PHP-related settings in the `location ~ \.php$` block if necessary.

Note: If you are using a CMS or framework like WordPress or Laravel, you may need additional configuration specific to your application.

When using Retrofit, it is possible to handle different API responses on different devices by implementing different response models for each device.

Here's how you can achieve this:

1. Create a base response model: Start by creating a base response model that represents the common fields in the API response. This model should include fields that are present in all API responses, regardless of the device.

2. Create device-specific response models: Next, create device-specific response models that extend the base response model. These models should include additional fields that are specific to each device. For example, if you have an API that returns different data for mobile and web devices, you can create separate response models for each device.

3. Use the appropriate response model: In your Retrofit service interface, define the API endpoint methods and specify the appropriate response model for each device. You can do this by using the `@Headers` annotation to set the `Accept` header based on the device type.

For example, if you have separate response models for mobile and web devices named `MobileResponse` and `WebResponse`, respectively, you can define the API endpoint methods as follows:

```java
@Headers("Accept: application/json")
@GET("api/mobile")
Call<MobileResponse> getMobileData();

@Headers("Accept: application/json")
@GET("api/web")
Call<WebResponse> getWebData();
```

4. Handle the response: When making API calls, Retrofit will automatically deserialize the response into the appropriate response model based on the device type. You can then handle the response accordingly in your callback or observer.

By following this approach, you can handle different API responses on different devices using Retrofit.

