In Java, you can catch multiple exception types in one catch block by using the pipe symbol (|) to separate the exception types. Here's an example:

```java
try {
    // code that may throw exceptions
} catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
    // handle IOException or SQLException
}
```

In this example, the catch block will handle both IOException and SQLException. If either of these exceptions is thrown in the try block, the catch block will be executed.

You can also use a common superclass or interface to catch multiple exception types. For example:

```java
try {
    // code that may throw exceptions
} catch (Exception e) {
    // handle any exception
}
```

In this case, the catch block will handle any exception that is a subclass of the Exception class. However, using a common superclass or interface may limit your ability to handle specific exceptions differently.

It's important to note that when catching multiple exception types in one catch block, the catch block can only have one parameter (e.g., `catch (IOException | SQLException e)`). If you need access to the specific exception object, you can use the `instanceof` operator to check the type and cast it accordingly.

