To ensure that the request was made from your own website, you can use a CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) token. Here's an example of how you can implement this:

1. Generate a CSRF token and store it in the user's session when they visit your website:
```php
session_start();
if (!isset($_SESSION['csrf_token'])) {
    $_SESSION['csrf_token'] = bin2hex(random_bytes(32));
}
```

2. Include the CSRF token in your AJAX requests:
```javascript
var csrfToken = "<?php echo $_SESSION['csrf_token']; ?>";

// Make AJAX request
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('POST', 'ajax_endpoint.php', true);
xhr.setRequestHeader('X-CSRF-Token', csrfToken);
xhr.send();
```

3. Validate the CSRF token on the server-side:
```php
session_start();

if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    // Check if the CSRF token is present and valid
    if (!empty($_SERVER['HTTP_X_CSRF_TOKEN']) && $_SERVER['HTTP_X_CSRF_TOKEN'] === $_SESSION['csrf_token']) {
        // Request is valid, process it
        // ...
    } else {
        // Invalid CSRF token, handle the error
        // ...
    }
}
```

By including and validating the CSRF token in your AJAX requests, you can ensure that the request was made from your own website and not from a malicious source.

