In this example, the `CustomException` class extends the built-in `Exception` class and adds an additional private property `$extraParam`. The constructor of the subclass accepts the extra parameter and sets it using the `parent::__construct()` method. The `getExtraParam()` method is added to retrieve the extra parameter value.

When throwing the exception, you can pass the extra parameter value as the third argument to the constructor. When catching the exception, you can access the extra parameter value using the `getExtraParam()` method.

To test if a string is URL encoded in PHP, you can use the `urldecode()` function and compare the original string with the decoded string. If they are the same, it means the string is not URL encoded. Here's an example:

