Ajax file upload is a technique that allows users to upload files to a server without refreshing the entire web page. It uses the XMLHttpRequest object in JavaScript to send the file data to the server asynchronously, allowing the user to continue interacting with the page while the file is being uploaded.

To implement Ajax file upload, you can follow these steps:

1. Create an HTML form with an input element of type "file" to allow the user to select the file they want to upload.
```html
<form id="uploadForm" enctype="multipart/form-data">
  <input type="file" name="file" id="fileInput">
  <input type="submit" value="Upload">
</form>
```

2. Attach an event listener to the form's submit event to handle the file upload.
```javascript
document.getElementById('uploadForm').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
  e.preventDefault(); // Prevent the form from submitting normally

  var fileInput = document.getElementById('fileInput');
  var file = fileInput.files[0]; // Get the selected file

  var formData = new FormData(); // Create a FormData object
  formData.append('file', file); // Append the file to the FormData object

  var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest(); // Create a new XMLHttpRequest object

  // Set up the event handler for the XMLHttpRequest object
  xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
    if (xhr.readyState === XMLHttpRequest.DONE) {
      if (xhr.status === 200) {
        // File upload successful
        console.log(xhr.responseText);
      } else {
        // File upload failed
        console.error(xhr.responseText);
      }
    }
  };

  // Open the XMLHttpRequest object and send the FormData object
  xhr.open('POST', 'upload.php', true);
  xhr.send(formData);
});
```

3. On the server-side, you need to handle the file upload request and save the uploaded file. This can be done using a server-side programming language like PHP, Node.js, or Python. Here's an example using PHP:
```php
<?php
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
  if (isset($_FILES['file'])) {
    $file = $_FILES['file'];

    // Check for errors during file upload
    if ($file['error'] === UPLOAD_ERR_OK) {
      $destination = 'uploads/' . $file['name'];
      move_uploaded_file($file['tmp_name'], $destination);
      echo 'File uploaded successfully.';
    } else {
      echo 'Error uploading file.';
    }
  } else {
    echo 'No file selected.';
  }
}
?>
```

Make sure to adjust the server-side code based on your specific requirements and programming language.

Note: Ajax file upload may not work in older browsers that do not support the XMLHttpRequest object or FormData object. In such cases, you can use a JavaScript library like jQuery or a file upload plugin that provides cross-browser compatibility.

In PHP, a leading backslash (\) before a class or namespace name is used to specify the absolute path of the class or namespace. It is called the "namespace separator" and is used to access classes or namespaces outside of the current namespace.

When a class or namespace is referenced without a leading backslash, PHP assumes that it is relative to the current namespace or the global namespace if no namespace is defined. However, if a leading backslash is used, PHP will always look for the class or namespace starting from the global namespace.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```php
namespace MyNamespace;

use AnotherNamespace\SomeClass;
use \AnotherNamespace\AnotherClass;

// Relative namespace
$object1 = new SomeClass(); // Resolves to MyNamespace\AnotherNamespace\SomeClass

// Absolute namespace
$object2 = new \AnotherNamespace\AnotherClass(); // Resolves to AnotherNamespace\AnotherClass
```

In the above example, when `SomeClass` is referenced without a leading backslash, PHP assumes it is relative to the current namespace `MyNamespace`. However, when `AnotherClass` is referenced with a leading backslash, PHP starts looking for it from the global namespace.

Using a leading backslash is particularly useful when you want to explicitly reference a class or namespace from the global namespace or when you want to avoid conflicts with classes or namespaces in the current namespace.

