The PostTooLargeException is an exception that is thrown when the size of the uploaded file exceeds the maximum allowed size specified in the server configuration.

In Laravel, this exception is handled by the `Handler` class, which is located in the `app/Exceptions` directory. By default, the `Handler` class includes a method called `render` that handles the exception and returns a response to the user.

To handle the PostTooLargeException, you can modify the `render` method in the `Handler` class. You can check if the exception is an instance of PostTooLargeException and return a custom response or redirect the user to a specific page.

Here's an example of how you can handle the PostTooLargeException in Laravel:

```php
use Illuminate\Http\Exceptions\PostTooLargeException;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Exceptions\Handler as ExceptionHandler;

class Handler extends ExceptionHandler
{
    // ...

    public function render($request, Exception $exception)
    {
        if ($exception instanceof PostTooLargeException) {
            // Handle the exception here
            return response()->view('errors.file-too-large', [], 422);
        }

        return parent::render($request, $exception);
    }

    // ...
}
```

In the example above, we check if the exception is an instance of PostTooLargeException. If it is, we return a custom response using the `view` method, passing the name of the view file ('errors.file-too-large') and the HTTP status code (422) as arguments.

You can create a custom view file to display an error message to the user, or you can redirect the user to a specific page using the `redirect` method.

Remember to import the PostTooLargeException class at the top of the file, along with the ExceptionHandler class.

