To create a PHP-like autoloader using Node.js, you can use the `require` function in Node.js along with some custom logic. Here's an example implementation:

1. Create a file called `autoloader.js`:

```javascript
const path = require('path');

class Autoloader {
  constructor() {
    this.namespaces = {};
  }

  registerNamespace(namespace, directory) {
    this.namespaces[namespace] = directory;
  }

  loadClass(className) {
    const namespace = className.split('\\')[0];
    const filePath = className.replace(/\\/g, '/') + '.js';

    if (this.namespaces[namespace]) {
      const fullPath = path.join(this.namespaces[namespace], filePath);
      require(fullPath);
    } else {
      throw new Error(`Namespace ${namespace} not registered.`);
    }
  }
}

module.exports = new Autoloader();
```

2. In your main application file, require the `autoloader.js` file and register your namespaces:

```javascript
const autoloader = require('./autoloader');

autoloader.registerNamespace('App', path.join(__dirname, 'app'));
```

3. Create a directory called `app` in the same directory as your main application file.

4. Inside the `app` directory, create a file called `MyClass.js`:

```javascript
class MyClass {
  constructor() {
    console.log('MyClass instantiated.');
  }
}

module.exports = MyClass;
```

5. In your main application file, you can now use the autoloader to load and instantiate the `MyClass`:

```javascript
const autoloader = require('./autoloader');

autoloader.loadClass('App\\MyClass');

const myObject = new App\MyClass();
```

When you run your Node.js application, it will automatically load and instantiate the `MyClass` using the autoloader.

