In PHP, both Singleton and Static classes are used to create a class that can only have one instance. However, there are some differences between the two approaches.

Singleton:
- A Singleton class allows only one instance of the class to be created.
- It provides a global point of access to the instance.
- The instance is created lazily, i.e., only when it is first requested.
- It can have instance methods and properties.
- It can implement interfaces and extend other classes.
- It can be extended by other classes.
- It can be mocked or replaced during unit testing.

Example of a Singleton class in PHP:

```php
class Singleton {
    private static $instance;

    private function __construct() {
        // private constructor to prevent direct instantiation
    }

    public static function getInstance() {
        if (self::$instance === null) {
            self::$instance = new self();
        }
        return self::$instance;
    }

    public function doSomething() {
        // do something
    }
}

$singleton = Singleton::getInstance();
$singleton->doSomething();
```

Static Class:
- A Static class cannot be instantiated, as it only contains static methods and properties.
- It provides a global point of access to its methods and properties.
- All methods and properties are shared among all instances of the class.
- It cannot implement interfaces or extend other classes.
- It cannot be extended by other classes.
- It cannot be mocked or replaced during unit testing.

Example of a Static class in PHP:

```php
class StaticClass {
    private static $property;

    private function __construct() {
        // private constructor to prevent instantiation
    }

    public static function getProperty() {
        return self::$property;
    }

    public static function setProperty($value) {
        self::$property = $value;
    }

    public static function doSomething() {
        // do something
    }
}

StaticClass::setProperty('value');
echo StaticClass::getProperty();
StaticClass::doSomething();
```

In summary, if you need a class that can have only one instance and can be extended or mocked, you should use the Singleton pattern. On the other hand, if you only need a class with static methods and properties that can be accessed globally, you can use a Static class.

