In PHP, &$string is a reference to a variable called $string. 

When you use the ampersand (&) before a variable name, it creates a reference to that variable instead of making a copy of its value. This means that any changes made to the referenced variable will also affect the original variable.

For example, if you have a function that takes a reference to a string as a parameter like this:

```php
function modifyString(&$string) {
    $string .= " is modified";
}

$text = "This string";
modifyString($text);
echo $text;
```

The output will be: "This string is modified". 

In this case, the function modifyString() modifies the original $text variable by appending " is modified" to it, even though it is passed by reference.
